# Appendix A Derivation of general rate law for saturating and inhibited secondary nucleation
https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.15932

As discussed at length in the literature Meisl et al. ( 2014 , 2016b ); Dear et al. ( 2020a ); Curk et al. ( 2024 ) , secondary nucleation in amyloid-β formation is well-modelled as the co-operative binding of two or more monomers to a catalytic site on fibril surfaces, and their subsequent conversion to a new fibril nucleus. The rate-limiting step of this conversion reaction pathway must be monomer-independent for Michaelis-Menten-like saturation effects to be observed in the secondary nucleation rate. If Aβxx monomers can inhibit Aβ42 secondary nucleation specifically, without also affecting primary nucleation, then this inhibition must be achieved competitively, by their also binding to secondary nucleation sites on the Aβ42 fibrils. What is not clear a priori is whether or not this binding is also co-operative, requiring multiple Aβxx monomers or even a mixture of Aβ42 and Aβxx monomers.

We will denote the conversion-competent clusters of Aβ42 monomers bound to catalytic sites on Aβ42 fibrils as M a ∗ M_{a}^{*} . For generality we will allow them to be of arbitrary minimum size n 2 ​ ( a ) n_{2}(a) . We will denote the Aβxx-containing species bound to such sites as M a I M_{a}^{I} . These consist predominantly of n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) n_{2}(aa) Aβ42 monomers and n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) n_{2}(ab) Aβxx monomers, with these numbers to be determined later. Finally, we write M a f M_{a}^{f} as the concentration of free (unbound) catalytic sites. The total mass concentration of Aβ42 fibrils can then be written as: M a = s a ​ ( M a f + M a ∗ + M a I ) , M_{a}=s_{a}(M_{a}^{f}+M_{a}^{*}+M_{a}^{I}), (28) where s a s_{a} is the stoichiometry of secondary nucleation sites, specifically, the number of monomeric subunits in a fibril per secondary nucleation site.

As discussed at length in previous publications Meisl et al. ( 2014 ); Dear et al. ( 2020a ) , Michaelis-Menten-type kinetics are a reasonable approximation to make for secondary nucleation in amyloid formation. Therefore, we make the simplifying assumption of pre-equilibrium or partial-equilibrium between bound and unbound states in the timescale of protein aggregation, i.e.: m a n 2 ​ ( a ) ​ M a f M a ∗ = K S ​ ( a ) n 2 ​ ( a ) , m a n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) ​ m b n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) ​ M a f M a I = K S ​ ( b ​ a ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) + n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) , \frac{m_{a}^{n_{2}(a)}M_{a}^{f}}{M_{a}^{*}}=K_{S}(a)^{n_{2}(a)},\qquad\frac{m_{a}^{n_{2}(aa)}m_{b}^{n_{2}(ab)}M_{a}^{f}}{M_{a}^{I}}=K_{S}(ba)^{n_{2}(aa)+n_{2}(ab)}, (29) where K S ​ ( a ) n 2 ​ ( a ) K_{S}(a)^{n_{2}(a)} and K S ​ ( b ​ a ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) + n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) K_{S}(ba)^{n_{2}(aa)+n_{2}(ab)} are the equilibrium dissociation constants for the unbinding of pure-Aβ42 clusters and of Aβxx-containing species from the catalytic sites. Note, if n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) = 0 n_{2}(aa)=0 and n 2 ​ ( b ​ a ) = 1 n_{2}(ba)=1 , this is just the dissociation constant for Aβxx monomers from a secondary nucleation site on an Aβ42 fibril.

Combining these equations allows us to express the total Aβ42 fibril mass concentration as: M a = s a ​ M a f ​ ( 1 + ( m a / K S ​ ( a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ) + ( m a / K S ​ ( b ​ a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) ​ ( m b / K S ​ ( b ​ a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) ) . M_{a}=s_{a}M_{a}^{f}\left(1+(m_{a}/K_{S}(a))^{n_{2}(a)}+(m_{a}/K_{S}(ba))^{n_{2}(aa)}(m_{b}/K_{S}(ba))^{n_{2}(ab)}\right). (30) Since we have seen that the presence of Aβxx protein does not accelerate the aggregation of Aβ42, rates of conversion of mixed clusters to Aβ42 fibrils must be far slower than that of homogeneous Aβ42 clusters. Therefore, to a good approximation the rate of generation of new Aβ42 fibrils by secondary nucleation is: r S = 2 ​ k c ​ M a ∗ = 2 ​ k c ​ M a f ​ ( m a / K S ​ ( a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ) , r_{S}=2k_{c}M_{a}^{*}=2k_{c}M_{a}^{f}(m_{a}/K_{S}(a))^{n_{2}(a)}, (31) where k c k_{c} is some conversion rate constant, this ultimately yields: r S = 2 ​ k 2 ​ ( a ) ​ m a ​ ( t ) n 2 ​ ( a ) ​ M a ​ ( t ) 1 + ( m a ​ ( t ) / K S ​ ( a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ) + ( m a / K S ​ ( b ​ a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ a ) ​ ( m b / K S ​ ( b ​ a ) ) n 2 ​ ( a ​ b ) , r_{S}=\frac{2k_{2}(a)m_{a}(t)^{n_{2}(a)}M_{a}(t)}{1+\left(m_{a}(t)/K_{S}(a)\right)^{n_{2}(a)}+(m_{a}/K_{S}(ba))^{n_{2}(aa)}(m_{b}/K_{S}(ba))^{n_{2}(ab)}}, (32) where k 2 = k c / s a ​ K S ​ ( a ) n 2 ​ ( a ) k_{2}=k_{c}/s_{a}K_{S}(a)^{n_{2}(a)} . We are additionally at liberty in the present context to set m b = m b ​ ( 0 ) m_{b}=m_{b}(0) because Aβ42 aggregation is completed before significant depletion of Aβxx monomers. Doing so yields finally Eq. ( 3 ).
